As an introverted creative, being self-employed and valuing one's privacy highly should not be a contradiction, but it often is. Most online sources and coaches recommend working with the (bad) tech giants and being extroverted. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Earn a blue checkmark on that service, be available 24/7, answer requests with a video of yourself, answer immediately. Video, video, video.
One third
For me, it is a year of change.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solutions and push them on everyone. I'm looking for new ways to run a business, and at the same time, I'm fighting my long-held belief that you have to do something in a certain way to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I cancelled Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I then also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good with that.
Recently, I have subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will relocate my business there in the coming weeks.
I transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for a regular email validation.
Three out of three.
